,"1515":"1515","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Brenchley,,Kent,England":"Brenchley, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1481–about 1538":"about 1481–about 1538","1489–1527":"1489–1527","1503–1557":"1503–1557","1509–1573":"1509–1573","1511–1556":"1511–1556","1511–1562":"1511–1562","1515–1559":"1515–1559","1481–1538":"1481–1538","about 1481":"about 1481","1481":"1481","about 1509":"about 1509","1503":"1503","1557":"1557","about 1538":"about 1538","1556":"1556","1511":"1511","1489":"1489","about 1503":"about 1503","about 1515":"about 1515","about 1502":"about 1502","1562":"1562","1573":"1573","about 1511":"about 1511","1509":"1509","1527":"1527","1538":"1538","1559":"1559","1515":"1515","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Brenchley,,Kent,England":"Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Anderson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ander(s)</i>, a northern Middle English form of   Andrew  , + <i>son</i> ‘son’. The frequency of the surname in Scotland is attributable, at least in part, to the fact that Saint Andrew is the patron saint of Scotland, so the personal name has long enjoyed great popularity there. Legend has it that the saint's relics were taken to Scotland in the 4th century by a certain Saint Regulus. In North America, this surname has absorbed many cognate or like-sounding surnames in other languages, notably Scandinavian (see 3 and 4 below), but also Ukrainian <b>Andreychenko</b> etc.","German: patronymic from the personal name   Anders  , hence a cognate of 1 above.","Americanized form (and a less common Swedish variant) of Swedish   Andersson  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Andrew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the usual vernacular English form (recorded from the 13th century onward) of the New Testament Greek personal name   Andreas  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Czech <b>Ondřej</b> (see   Ondrey  ) and Albanian   Ndreu  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Andrews  ).","History: The surname Andrew was first brought to North America from England by Robert Andrew (died 1668), who settled in Boxford, MA."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Anderson was born about 1481, in Brenchley, Kent, England. She married Stephen Foreman about 1502, in Brenchley, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1538, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1481–about 1538":"umbes 1481–umbes 1538","1489–1527":"1489–1527","1503–1557":"1503–1557","1509–1573":"1509–1573","1511–1556":"1511–1556","1511–1562":"1511–1562","1515–1559":"1515–1559","1481–1538":"1481–1538","about 1481":"umbes 1481","1481":"1481","about 1509":"umbes 1509","1503":"1503","1557":"1557","about 1538":"umbes 1538","1556"